// Package-import trait-signature REJECT oracle (RAII-2 #1295).
//
// `hew::sinkres` exports a trait `Sink` whose bodyless `put(self, item: Sticky)`
// takes a sibling `#[resource]` by value WITHOUT `consume`. A bodyless trait
// method signature is an invisible-body boundary: dispatching impls may disagree
// on whether `item` is borrowed or consumed, so the disposition must be pinned
// with `consume`. Leaving it unannotated is a drop-safety bypass (double-free or
// leak depending on what the impl does).
//
// The root and file-flattened lowering passes already reject this. This oracle
// proves the discipline ALSO fires when the trait arrives via a PACKAGE import:
// the importer lowers `sinkres`'s items and must reject the unannotated
// `item: Sticky` with `ResourceBoundaryParamMustConsume`, NOT silently swallow
// the imported trait (the imported-module item loop previously had no trait arm
// and let the boundary through).
//
// Harness verb: hew check (negative — see run.sh). Asserts the boundary
// diagnostic fires at HIR-lowering time on the imported trait signature.
import hew::sinkres::{Sink};

fn main() {
    println("unreachable: check must reject the imported trait boundary");
}
